# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: route-reflectors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] An **autonomous system** (**AS**) is a collection of connected Internet Protocol (IP) routing prefixes under the control of one or more network operators on behalf of a single administrative entity or domain, that presents a common and clearly defined routing policy to the Internet.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Each AS is assigned an **autonomous system number** (**ASN**), for use in Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) routing.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] ASNs are assigned to local Internet registries (LIRs) and end-user organizations by their respective regional Internet registries (RIRs), which in turn receive blocks of ASNs for reassignment from the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA).
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] The IANA also maintains a registry of ASNs which are reserved for private use (and should therefore not be announced to the global Internet).
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Originally, the definition required control by a single entity, typically an Internet service provider (ISP) or a very large organization with independent connections to multiple networks, that adhered to a single and clearly defined routing policy.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] In March 1996, the newer definition came into use because multiple organizations can run BGP using private ASNs to an ISP that connects all those organizations to the Internet.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Even though there may be multiple autonomous systems supported by the ISP, the Internet only sees the routing policy of the ISP.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] That ISP must have an officially registered ASN.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Until 2007, ASNs were defined as 16-bit integers, which allowed for a maximum of 65,536 assignments.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Since then, the IANA has begun to also assign 32-bit AS numbers to regional Internet registries.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] These numbers are written preferably as simple integers, in a notation referred to as "asplain", ranging from 0 to 4,294,967,295 (hexadecimal 0xFFFF FFFF).
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Or, alternatively, in the form called "asdot+" which looks like *x.y*, where *x* and *y* are 16-bit numbers.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Numbers of the form *0.y* are exactly the old 16-bit AS numbers.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] The special 16-bit ASN 23456 ("AS_TRANS") was assigned by IANA as a placeholder for 32-bit ASN values for the case when 32-bit-ASN capable routers ("new BGP speakers") send BGP messages to routers with older BGP software ("old BGP speakers") which do not understand the new 32-bit ASNs.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] The first and last ASNs of the original 16-bit integers (0 and 65,535) and the last ASN of the 32-bit numbers (4,294,967,295) are reserved and should not be used by operators; AS0 is used by all five RIRs to invalidate unallocated space.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] ASNs 64,496 to 64,511 of the original 16-bit range and 65,536 to 65,551 of the 32-bit range are reserved for use in documentation.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] By December 2020, the number of allocated ASNs exceeded 100,000.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] As of 2025, there are roughly 120,000 allocated ASNs.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] ASNs are assigned in blocks by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) to regional Internet registries (RIRs).
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] The appropriate RIR then assigns ASNs to entities within its designated area from the block assigned by IANA.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Entities wishing to receive an ASN must complete the application process of their RIR, LIR or upstream service provider and be approved before being assigned an ASN.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Current IANA ASN assignments to RIRs can be found on the IANA website.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] RIRs, as part of NRO, can revoke AS numbers as part of their Internet governance abilities.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Autonomous systems (AS) can be grouped into four categories, depending on their connectivity and operating policy.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] *stub*: An AS that is connected to only one other AS.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] This may be an apparent waste of an AS number if the network's routing policy is the same as its upstream AS's.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] However, the stub AS may have peering with other autonomous systems that is not reflected in public route-view servers.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Specific examples include private interconnections in the financial and transportation sectors.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] *transit*: An AS that acts as an intermediary between at least two ASes is called a transit.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Since not all ASes are directly connected with every other AS, a transit AS carries data traffic between one AS to another AS to which it has links.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] A transit AS can be and typically is multihomed.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] *internet exchange point* (IX or IXP): A physical infrastructure through which different networks (autonomous systems), typically Internet service providers (ISPs) and content delivery networks (CDNs), exchange Internet traffic.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] These are often groups of local ISPs that band together to exchange data by splitting the costs of a local networking hub, avoiding the higher network costs and bandwidth charges of a private interconnect or transit AS.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] IXP ASNs are usually transparent, meaning they are not visible in the BGP AS path.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] By having presence at an IXP, ASes shorten the transit path to other participating ASes, thereby reducing network latency and improving round-trip delay.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Autonomous systems can be included in one or more AS-SETs, for example AS-SET of RIPE NCC "AS-12655" has AS1, AS2 and AS3 as its members, but AS1 is also included in other sets in ARIN (AS-INCAPSULA) and APNIC (AS-IMCL).
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Other AS-SET sources can be RADB, LEVEL3 (tier 1 network now called Lumen Technologies) and also ARIN has the ARIN-NONAUTH source of AS-SETs.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] AS-SETs are created by network operators in an Internet Routing Registry (IRR), like other route objects, and can be included in other AS-SETs and even form cycles.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] AS-SET names usually start with "AS-", but can also have a hierarchical name.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] For example, the administrator of AS 64500 may create an AS-SET called "AS64500:AS-UPSTREAMS", to avoid conflict with other similarly named AS-SETs.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Since early 2023, the RIPE NCC enforces hierarchical AS-SET names for new objects, due to issues with conflicts between different IRR databases and potential malicious use based on the AS-SET name.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Other IRR databases have soon followed with the same restriction.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] AS-SETs are often used to simplify management of published routing policies.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] A routing policy is published in the IRR using "import" and "export" (or the newer "mp-import" and "mp-export") attributes, which each contain the source or destination ASN, and the ASN imported or exported.
[src:route-reflectors/autonomous-system-internet] Instead of single ASNs, AS-SETs can be referenced in these attributes, which simplifies management of complex routing policies.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] BGP used for routing within an autonomous system is called **Interior Border Gateway Protocol** (**iBGP**).
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In contrast, the Internet application of the protocol is called **Exterior Border Gateway Protocol** (**EBGP**).
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In January 1989, at the 12th IETF meeting in Austin, Texas, Yakov Rekhter, Len Bosack, and Kirk Lougheed sat down at a table to design what ultimately became the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The initial BGP design was recorded on two napkins, hence often referenced to as the “Two-Napkin Protocol”.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The design on the napkins was expanded to three hand-written sheets of paper from which the first interoperable BGP implementation was quickly developed.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] A photocopy of these three sheets of paper now hangs on the wall of a routing protocol development area at Cisco Systems in Milpitas, California.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In the same year, RFC 1105 was published, and the BGP protocol (in various forms) has been in use on the Internet since 1994.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Half a year after the initial publication, the protocol definition was changed in 1990 with the publication of RFC 1136.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In October 1991, BGP version 3 was defined in RFC 1267, obsoleting the two earlier versions.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In 1994, the current version (BGP4), was published as RFC 1654.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Its definition was replaced in March 1995 by RFC 1771.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In January 2006, RFC 4271 was published, which currently is the latest definition of BGP4 (although updated by many other RFCs).
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] RFC 4271 corrected errors, clarified ambiguities and updated the specification with common industry practices.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The major enhancement of BGP4 was the support for Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) and use of route aggregation to decrease the size of routing tables.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In its native form, the BGP4 protocol can only work with IPv4 addresses.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Since the publication of RFC 2283 in 1998, routing information about a wide range of "address families" (IPv4, IPv6, IPX, etc.) can be carried.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The 'Multiprotocol Extensions' have been updated in 2000 with RFC 2858 and finally in 2007 with RFC 4760.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] With these extensions, the protocol is also referred to as Multiprotocol BGP (MP-BGP).
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] BGP neighbors, called peers, are established by manual configuration among routers to create a TCP session on port 179.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] A BGP speaker sends 19-byte keep-alive messages every 30 seconds (protocol default value, tunable) to maintain the connection.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Among routing protocols, BGP is unique in using TCP as its transport protocol.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] When BGP runs between two peers in the same autonomous system (AS), it is referred to as *Internal BGP* (*iBGP* or *Interior Border Gateway Protocol*).
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] When it runs between different autonomous systems, it is called *External BGP* (*eBGP* or *Exterior Border Gateway Protocol*).
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Routers on the boundary of one AS exchanging information with another AS are called *border* or *edge routers* or simply *eBGP peers* and are typically connected directly, while *iBGP peers* can be interconnected through other intermediate routers.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Other deployment topologies are also possible, such as running eBGP peering inside a VPN tunnel, allowing two remote sites to exchange routing information in a secure and isolated manner.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] These route-propagation rules effectively require that all iBGP peers inside an AS are interconnected in a full mesh with iBGP sessions.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] How routes are propagated can be controlled in detail via the *route-maps* mechanism.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This mechanism consists of a set of rules.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Each rule describes, for routes matching some given criteria, what action should be taken.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The action could be to drop the route, or it could be to modify some attributes of the route before inserting it in the routing table.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] During the peering handshake, when OPEN messages are exchanged, BGP speakers can negotiate optional capabilities of the session, including multiprotocol extensions and various recovery modes.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] If the multiprotocol extensions to BGP are negotiated at the time of creation, the BGP speaker can prefix the Network Layer Reachability Information (NLRI) it advertises with an address family prefix.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] These families include the IPv4 (default), IPv6, IPv4/IPv6 Virtual Private Networks and multicast BGP.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Increasingly, BGP is used as a generalized signaling protocol to carry information about routes that may not be part of the global Internet, such as VPNs.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In order to make decisions in its operations with peers, a BGP peer uses a simple finite-state machine (FSM) that consists of six states: Idle; Connect; Active; OpenSent; OpenConfirm; and Established.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] For each peer-to-peer session, a BGP implementation maintains a state variable that tracks which of these six states the session is in.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The BGP defines the messages that each peer should exchange in order to change the session from one state to another.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In the Idle state, BGP initializes all resources, refuses all inbound BGP connection attempts and initiates a TCP connection to the peer.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In the Connect state, the router waits for the TCP connection to complete and transitions to the OpenSent state if successful.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] If unsuccessful, it starts the ConnectRetry timer and transitions to the Active state upon expiration.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In the Active state, the router resets the ConnectRetry timer to zero and returns to the Connect state.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In the OpenSent state, the router sends an Open message and waits for one in return in order to transition to the OpenConfirm state.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Keepalive messages are exchanged and, upon successful receipt, the router is placed into the Established state.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In the Established state, the router can send and receive: Keepalive; Update; and Notification messages to and from its peer.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In the simplest arrangement, all routers within a single AS and participating in BGP routing must be configured in a full mesh: each router must be configured as a peer to every other router.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This causes scaling problems, since the number of required connections grows quadratically with the number of routers involved.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] To alleviate the problem, BGP implements two options: route reflectors (RFC 4456) and BGP confederations (RFC 5065).
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The following discussion of basic update processing assumes a full iBGP mesh.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] A given BGP router may accept network-layer reachability information (NLRI) updates from multiple neighbors and advertise NLRI to the same, or a different set, of neighbors.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The physical storage and structure of these conceptual tables are decided by the implementer of the BGP code.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Their structure is not visible to other BGP routers, although they usually can be interrogated with management commands on the local router.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] It is quite common, for example, to store the `Adj-RIB-In`, `Adj-RIB-Out` and the `Loc-RIB` together in the same data structure, with additional information attached to the RIB entries.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] BGP submits the routes that it considers best to the main routing table process.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Depending on the implementation of that process, the BGP route is not necessarily selected.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] For example, a directly connected prefix, learned from the router's own hardware, is usually most preferred.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] As long as that directly connected route's interface is active, the BGP route to the destination will not be put into the routing table.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Once the interface goes down and there are no more preferred routes, the Loc-RIB route would be installed in the main routing table.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] BGP carries the information with which rules inside BGP-speaking routers can make policy decisions.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The BGP standard specifies a number of decision factors, more than the ones that are used by any other common routing process, for selecting NLRI to go into the Loc-RIB.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The first decision point for evaluating NLRI is that its next-hop attribute must be reachable (or resolvable).
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Another way of saying the next-hop must be reachable is that there must be an active route, already in the main routing table of the router, to the prefix in which the next-hop address is reachable.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Next, for each neighbor, the BGP process applies various standard and implementation-dependent criteria to decide which routes conceptually should go into the Adj-RIB-In.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The neighbor could send several possible routes to a destination, but the first level of preference is at the neighbor level.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Only one route to each destination will be installed in the conceptual Adj-RIB-In.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This process will also delete, from the Adj-RIB-In, any routes that are withdrawn by the neighbor.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Whenever a conceptual Adj-RIB-In changes, the main BGP process decides if any of the neighbor's new routes are preferred to routes already in the Loc-RIB.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] If a given route is withdrawn by a neighbor, and there is no other route to that destination, the route is removed from the Loc-RIB and no longer sent by BGP to the main routing table manager.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] If the router does not have a route to that destination from any non-BGP source, the withdrawn route will be removed from the main routing table.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] As long as there is a tie, the route selection process moves to the next step.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The local preference, weight, and other criteria can be manipulated by local configuration and software capabilities.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Such manipulation, although commonly used, is outside the scope of the standard.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] For example, the *community* attribute (see below) is not directly used by the BGP selection process.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The BGP neighbor process can have a rule to set local preference or another factor based on a manually programmed rule to set the attribute if the community value matches some pattern-matching criterion.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] If the route was learned from an external peer the per-neighbor BGP process computes a local preference value from local policy rules and then compares the local preference of all routes from the neighbor.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] BGP communities are attribute tags that can be applied to incoming or outgoing prefixes to achieve some common goal.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] While it is common to say that BGP allows an administrator to set policies on how prefixes are handled by ISPs, this is generally not possible, strictly speaking.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] For instance, BGP natively has no concept to allow one AS to tell another AS to restrict advertisement of a prefix to only North American peering customers.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Instead, an ISP generally publishes a list of well-known or proprietary communities with a description for each one, which essentially becomes an agreement of how prefixes are to be treated.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The customer simply adjusts their configuration to include the correct community or communities for each route, and the ISP is responsible for controlling who the prefix is advertised to.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The end user has no technical ability to enforce correct actions being taken by the ISP, though problems in this area are generally rare and accidental.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] It is a common tactic for end customers to use BGP communities (usually ASN:70,80,90,100) to control the local preference the ISP assigns to advertised routes instead of using MED (the effect is similar).
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The community attribute is transitive, but communities applied by the customer very rarely propagate outside the next-hop AS.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Not all ISPs give out their communities to the public.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The BGP Extended Community Attribute was added in 2006, in order to extend the range of such attributes and to provide a community attribute structuring by means of a type field.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The extended format consists of one or two octets for the type field, followed by seven or six octets for the respective community attribute content.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The IANA administers the registry for BGP Extended Communities Types.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The Extended Communities Attribute itself is a transitive optional BGP attribute.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] A bit in the *Type* field within the attribute decides whether the encoded extended community is of a transitive or non-transitive nature.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The IANA registry therefore provides different number ranges for the attribute types.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Due to the extended attribute range, its usage can be manifold.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] RFC 4360 exemplarily defines the "Two-Octet AS Specific Extended Community", the "IPv4 Address Specific Extended Community", the "Opaque Extended Community", the "Route Target Community", and the "Route Origin Community".
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] A number of BGP QoS drafts also use this Extended Community Attribute structure for inter-domain QoS signalling.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] With the introduction of 32-bit AS numbers, some issues were immediately obvious with the community attribute that only defines a 16-bit ASN field, which prevents the matching between this field and the real ASN value.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Since 2014, extended communities are compatible with 32-bit ASNs.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] To accommodate 32-bit AS numbers in BGP Communities, a Large Community attribute of 12 bytes was defined, divided in three field of 4 bytes each (AS:function:parameter).
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] MEDs, defined in the main BGP standard, were originally intended to show to another neighbor AS the advertising AS's preference as to which of several links are preferred for inbound traffic.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Another application of MEDs is to advertise the value, typically based on delay, of multiple ASs that have a presence at an IXP, that they impose to send traffic to some destination.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Some routers (like Juniper) will use the Metric from OSPF to set MED.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] All BGP messages share the following header layout.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Included for compatibility, MUST be set to all ones.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Total length of the message in octets, including the header.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] With an *Open* packet, a BGP session may be initiated.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Timeout timer, used to calculate KeepAlive messages.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Total length of the Parameters field in octets.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] field is zero, there are no parameters in the message.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This field is used to convey the capabilities the sender of this packet has to the peer.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] After the initial exchange, only differences (add/change/remove) are sent.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Length of the following withdrawn routes.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Length of the following path attributes.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Reachability information, specified as a series of <length, prefix> tuples.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] If there is an error, it is because one of the fields in the OPEN or UPDATE message does not match between the peers.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] For example: BGP version mismatch, or the peering router expects a different 'My AS'.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The router then sends a Notification message to the peer indicating why the error occurred.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] An error in the communication usually leads to the teardown of the BGP session.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] To avoid a cascade of sessions being terminated due to a single error, which can happen in complex scenarios with routers with limited capabilities, extra effort is taken to isolate the problem and keep most sessions going.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] A value indicating the type or origin of the error.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] A value specifying which error occurred.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Optional data to help diagnose the problem.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] KeepAlive messages are sent periodically, by both peers of a session, to verify that the remote peer is still alive.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] They should be sent at intervals of one third the `holdtime`.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] A keep-alive packet has no data content.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] An addition to the initial BGP message types is route-refresh, which allows for soft updating of `Adj-RIB-in`, without resetting the connection.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Before making use of this feature, the capability 'Route Refresh Capability (2)' should be specified in the 'Open' message.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Fine-grained routing updates may be acquired when the capability 'Enhanced Route Refresh Capability (70)' is also given.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This field indicates what kind of route-refresh message this is.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This field provides additional information about the type of the Network Layer Reachability Information (NLRI) carried in the attribute.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] An autonomous system with internal BGP (iBGP) must have all of its iBGP peers connect to each other in a full mesh (where everyone speaks to everyone directly).
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This full-mesh configuration requires that each router maintain a session with every other router.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In large networks, this number of sessions may degrade the performance of routers, due to either a lack of memory or high CPU process requirements.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This approach, similar to OSPF's DR/BDR feature, provides large networks with added iBGP scalability.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In a fully meshed iBGP network of 10 routers, 90 individual CLI statements (spread throughout all routers in the topology) are needed just to define the remote-AS of each peer: this quickly becomes a headache to manage.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] An RR topology can cut these 90 statements down to 18, offering a viable solution for the larger networks administered by ISPs.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] An RR is a single point of failure, therefore at least a second RR may be configured in order to provide redundancy.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] As it is an additional peer for the other 10 routers, it approximately doubles the number of CLI statements, requiring an additional 11 × 2 − 2 = 20 statements in this case.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In a BGP multipath environment, the additional RR can also benefit the network by adding local routing throughput if the RRs are acting as traditional routers instead of just a dedicated RR server role.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] RRs and confederations both reduce the number of iBGP peers to each router and thus reduce processing overhead.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] RRs are a pure performance-enhancing technique, while confederations can also be used to implement more fine-grained policy.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The *cluster ID* is then attached to every route advertised by the RR to its client or non-client peers.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] A cluster ID is a cumulative, non-transitive BGP attribute, and every RR must prepend the local cluster ID to the cluster list to avoid routing loops.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Confederations are sets of autonomous systems.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In common practice, only one of the confederation AS numbers is seen by the Internet as a whole.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Confederations are used in very large networks where a large AS can be configured to encompass smaller, more manageable internal ASs.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The confederated AS is composed of multiple ASs.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Each confederated AS alone has iBGP fully meshed and has connections to other ASs inside the confederation.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Even though these ASs have eBGP peers to ASs within the confederation, the ASs exchange routing as if they used iBGP.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In this way, the confederation preserves next hop, metric, and local preference information.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] To the outside world, the confederation appears to be a single AS.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] With this solution, iBGP transit AS problems can be resolved as iBGP requires a full mesh between all BGP routers: a large number of TCP sessions and unnecessary duplication of routing traffic.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Confederations can be used in conjunction with route reflectors.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Both confederations and route reflectors can be subject to persistent oscillation unless specific design rules, affecting both BGP and the interior routing protocol, are followed.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Additionally, route reflectors and BGP confederations were not designed to ease BGP router configuration.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Nevertheless, these are common tools for experienced BGP network architects.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] These tools may be combined, for example, as a hierarchy of route reflectors.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The routing tables managed by a BGP implementation are adjusted continually to reflect actual changes in the network, such as links or routers going down and coming back up.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In the network as a whole, it is normal for these changes to happen almost continuously, but for any particular router or link, changes are expected to be relatively infrequent.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] If a router is misconfigured or mismanaged, then it may get into a rapid cycle between down and up states.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This pattern of repeated withdrawal and re-announcement, known as route flapping can cause excessive activity in all the other routers that know about the cycling entity, as the same route is continually injected and withdrawn from the routing tables.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The BGP design is such that delivery of traffic may not function while routes are being updated.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] On the Internet, a BGP routing change may cause outages for several minutes.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] A feature known as *route flap damping* is built into many BGP implementations, in an attempt to mitigate the effects of route flapping.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Without damping, the excessive activity can cause a heavy processing load on routers, which may in turn delay updates on other routes, and so affect overall routing stability.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] With damping, a route's flapping is exponentially decayed.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] At the first instance, when a route becomes unavailable and quickly reappears, damping does not take effect, so as to maintain the normal fail-over times of BGP.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] At the second occurrence, BGP shuns that prefix for a certain length of time; subsequent occurrences are ignored exponentially longer.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] After the abnormalities have ceased and a suitable length of time has passed for the offending route, prefixes can be reinstated with a clean slate.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Damping can also mitigate denial-of-service attacks.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] It is also suggested that route flap damping is a feature more desirable if implemented to Exterior Border Gateway Protocol Sessions (eBGP sessions or simply called exterior peers) and not on Interior Border Gateway Protocol Sessions (iBGP sessions or simply called internal peers).
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] With this approach when a route flaps inside an autonomous system, it is not propagated to the external ASs – flapping a route to an eBGP will cause a chain of flapping for the particular route throughout the backbone.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This method also successfully avoids the overhead of route flap damping for iBGP sessions.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Subsequent research has shown that flap damping can actually lengthen convergence times in some cases, and can cause interruptions in connectivity even when links are not flapping.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Moreover, as backbone links and router processors have become faster, some network architects have suggested that flap damping may not be as important as it used to be, since changes to the routing table can be handled much faster by routers.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This has led the RIPE Routing Working Group to write, "With the current implementations of BGP flap damping, the application of flap damping in ISP networks is NOT recommended. ...
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] If flap damping is implemented, the ISP operating that network will cause side-effects to their customers and the Internet users of their customers' content and services ... .
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] One of the largest problems faced by BGP, and indeed the Internet infrastructure as a whole, is the growth of the Internet routing table.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] If the global routing table grows to the point where some older, less capable routers cannot cope with the memory requirements or the CPU load of maintaining the table, these routers will cease to be effective gateways between the parts of the Internet they connect.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In addition, and perhaps even more importantly, larger routing tables take longer to stabilize after a major connectivity change, leaving network service unreliable, or even unavailable, in the interim.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Until late 2001, the global routing table was growing exponentially, threatening an eventual widespread breakdown of connectivity.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In an attempt to prevent this, ISPs cooperated in keeping the global routing table as small as possible by using Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) and route aggregation.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] While this slowed the growth of the routing table to a linear process for several years, with the expanded demand for multihoming by end-user networks, the growth was once again superlinear by the middle of 2004.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] A Y2K-like overflow triggered in 2014 for those models that were not appropriately updated.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] While a full IPv4 BGP table as of August 2014 (512k day) was in excess of 512,000 prefixes, many older routers had a limit of 512k (512,000–524,288) routing table entries.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] On August 12, 2014, outages resulting from full tables hit eBay, LastPass and Microsoft Azure, among others.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] A number of Cisco routers commonly in use had TCAM, a form of high-speed content-addressable memory, for storing BGP advertised routes.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] On impacted routers, the TCAM was by default allocated as 512k IPv4 routes and 256k IPv6 routes.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] While the reported number of IPv6 advertised routes was only about 20k, the number of advertised IPv4 routes reached the default limit, causing a spillover effect as routers attempted to compensate for the issue by using slow software routing (as opposed to fast hardware routing via TCAM).
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The main method for dealing with this issue involves operators changing the TCAM allocation to allow more IPv4 entries by reallocating some of the TCAM reserved for IPv6 routes, which requires a reboot on most routers.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The 512k problem was predicted by a number of IT professionals.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The actual allocations, which pushed the number of routes above 512k, were the announcement of about 15,000 new routes in short order, starting at 07:48 UTC.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Almost all of these routes were to Verizon Autonomous Systems 701 and 705, created as a result of the deaggregation of larger blocks, introducing thousands of new */24* routes, and making the routing table reach 515,000 entries.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] The new routes appear to have been reaggregated within 5 minutes, but instability across the Internet apparently continued for a number of hours.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Even if Verizon had not caused the routing table to exceed 512k entries in the short spike, it would have soon happened through natural growth.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Route summarization is often used to improve aggregation of the BGP global routing table, thereby reducing the necessary table size in routers of an AS.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This all counts as AS1 announcing four routes.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] At AS1, it will either be dropped or a destination unreachable ICMP message will be sent back, depending on the configuration of AS1's routers.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] If AS2 now wants to send data to prefix *172.16.192.0/18*, it will be dropped or a destination unreachable ICMP message will be sent back at the routers of AS2 (not AS1 as before), because *172.16.192.0/18* is not in the routing table.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In 1995, the first BGP-4 specification coded AS numbers on 16 bits, for 64,510 possible public AS numbers.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In 2011, only 15,000 AS numbers were still available, and projections were envisioning a complete depletion of available AS numbers in September 2013.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] In 2007 already, the AS coding was extended from 16 to 32 bits, while retaining the 16-bit AS range (0 to 65535) and its reserved AS numbers.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This now allows up to 4 billion available AS numbers.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] An additional private AS range is also defined.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] To allow the traversal of router groups not able to manage those new ASNs, the new attribute **AS4_PATH** (optional transitive) and the special 16-bit ASN **AS_TRANS** (AS23456) is used.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Another factor contributing to the growth of the routing table is the need for load balancing of multi-homed networks.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] It is not a trivial task to balance the inbound traffic to a multi-homed network across its multiple inbound paths, due to limitations of the BGP route selection process.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] For a multi-homed network, if it announces the same network blocks across all of its BGP peers, the result may be that one or several of its inbound links become congested while the other links remain under-utilized, because external networks all picked that set of congested paths as optimal.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Like most other routing protocols, BGP does not detect congestion.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] Such cases will increase the number of routes as seen on the global BGP table.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] One method to address the routing table issue associated with load balancing is to deploy Locator/Identifier Separation Protocol (BGP/LISP) gateways within an Internet exchange point to allow ingress traffic engineering across multiple links.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This technique does not increase the number of routes seen on the global BGP table.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] By design, routers running BGP accept advertised routes from other BGP routers by default.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p01] This allows for automatic and decentralized routing of traffic across the Internet, but it also leaves the Internet potentially vulnerable to accidental or malicious disruption, known as BGP hijacking.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Multiprotocol Extensions for BGP (MBGP), sometimes referred to as Multiprotocol BGP or Multicast BGP and defined in RFC 4760, is an extension to BGP that allows different types of addresses (known as address families) to be distributed in parallel.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Whereas standard BGP supports only IPv4 unicast addresses, Multiprotocol BGP supports IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and it supports unicast and multicast variants of each.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Multiprotocol BGP allows information about the topology of IP multicast-capable routers to be exchanged separately from the topology of normal IPv4 unicast routers.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Thus, it allows a multicast routing topology different from the unicast routing topology.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Although MBGP enables the exchange of inter-domain multicast routing information, other protocols, such as the Protocol Independent Multicast family, are needed to build trees and forward multicast traffic.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Another extension to BGP is multipath routing.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] This typically requires identical MED, weight, origin, and AS-path, although some implementations provide the ability to relax the AS-path checking to only expect an equal path length rather than the actual AS numbers in the path being expected to match too.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] This can then be extended further with features like Cisco's dmzlink-bw which enables a ratio of traffic sharing based on bandwidth values configured on individual links.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] By default, BGP only supports the advertisement of a single locally selected best path to its neighbors through its Update messages.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] RFC 7911 defines the **ADD-PATH** extension, which allows a BGP speaker to advertise multiple paths for the same destination to peers.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] One application for this is when using route reflectors (RRs), because then the RR can advertise all known route paths to its clients, instead of sending only a single route it selected based on its local decision process, which is likely not the best path for all of its clients.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] BGP4 is standard for Internet routing and required of most Internet service providers (ISPs) to establish routing between one another.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Very large private IP networks use BGP internally.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] An example use case is the joining of a number of large Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) networks when OSPF by itself does not scale to the size required.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Another reason to use BGP is multihoming a network for better redundancy, either to multiple access points to a single ISP or to multiple ISPs.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Routers, especially small ones intended for small office/home office (SOHO) use, may not include BGP capability.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Other commercial routers may need a specific software executable image that supports BGP, or a license that enables it.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Devices marketed as layer-3 switches are less likely to support BGP than devices marketed as routers, but many high-end layer-3 switches can run BGP.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Products marketed as switches may have a size limitation on BGP tables that is far smaller than a full Internet table plus internal routes.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] A BGP router used only for a network with a single point of entry to the Internet may have a much smaller routing table size (and hence RAM and CPU requirements) than a multihomed network.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Even simple multihoming can have a modest routing table size.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] The actual amount of memory required in a BGP router depends on the amount of BGP information exchanged with other BGP speakers and the way in which the particular router stores BGP information.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] The router may have to keep more than one copy of a route, so it can manage different policies for route advertising and acceptance to a specific neighboring AS.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] The term *view* is often used for these different policy relationships on a running router.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] If one router implementation takes more memory per route than another implementation, this may be a legitimate design choice, trading processing speed against memory.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] A full IPv4 BGP table as of September 2025 is in excess of one million prefixes.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Large ISPs may add another 50% for internal and customer routes.
[src:route-reflectors/bgp-confederation-p02] Again, depending on implementation, separate tables may be kept for each view of a different peer AS.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] Convergence is an important notion for a set of routers that engage in dynamic routing.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] All interior gateway protocols rely on convergence to function properly.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] "To have, or be, converged" is the normal state of an operational autonomous system.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] The Exterior Gateway Routing Protocol BGP typically never converges because the Internet is too big for changes to be communicated fast enough.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] When a routing protocol process is enabled, every participating router will attempt to exchange information about the topology of the network.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] The extent of this information exchange, the way it is sent and received, and the type of information required vary widely depending on the routing protocol in use, see e.g.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] A state of convergence is achieved once all routing protocol-specific information has been distributed to all routers participating in the routing protocol process.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] Any change in the network that affects routing tables will break the convergence temporarily until this change has been successfully communicated to all other routers.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] RIP is a routing protocol that converges so slowly that even a network of a few routers can take a couple of minutes to converge.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] In case of a new route being advertised, triggered updates can speed up RIP's convergence but to flush a route that previously existed takes longer due to the holddown timers in use.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] OSPF is an example of a fast-converging routing protocol.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] A network of a few OSPF routers can converge in a matter of seconds.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] Certain configuration and hardware conditions will prevent a network from ever converging.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] For instance, a "flapping" interface (an interface that frequently changes its state between "up" and "down") might cause conflicting information to propagate throughout the network so the routers never agree on its current state.
[src:route-reflectors/convergence-routing] Under certain circumstances it might be desirable to withhold detailed routing information from parts of the network via route aggregation, thereby speeding up convergence of the topological information shared by all routers.
[src:route-reflectors/multiprotocol-bgp] Although MBGP enables the exchange of inter-domain multicast routing information, other protocols such as the Protocol Independent Multicast family are needed to build trees and forward multicast traffic.
